In Anſwer to which, I ſay it is true, Re hearings may be had in Courts of Equity;
As to Rehearings in the ſame Court where the miſtaken Decree was made. But I have heard it ſaid by a Court of Equity, That though Bills of Re-view were Matter of Right, yet Re-hearings were Matter of Favour only; and I have known ſome Cauſes have been often Re-heard, and other Cauſes that I thought deſerved it, could not obtain that Favour of being once Re-heard; and a Rehearing is not to be had after the Decree is Regularly ſign'd and inroll'd, though it be ever ſo erroneous or miſtaken: So that if a Re-hearing be had at all, it is, for the moſt part, before the Party or Parties that made the ſuppoſed miſtaken Decree: And though it is not to be denied, but a Man may alter his Opinion upon a Re-hearing; yet it was once the Opinion of the Commons in Parliament, as appears on the Roll, 21 E. 3. Nu. 26. (according to Cotten's Abridgment,) That it is not likely a Man will have a good Conceit againſt his own Opinion; and that was given as a Reaſon by the Commons in their Petition, That erroneous Judgments in the Exchequer ſhould be Redreſs'd in the King's Bench, the Court of Exchequer before that time making as if they would rectifie their own Errors: And the King's Anſwer to that Petition was, That he would grant Commiſſions to examine and correct the Errors of the Exchequer: but that did not ſatisfie; and after ſeveral attempts it was Enacted, 31 E 3. cap. 12. That the Chancellor and Treaſurer calling ſuch Judges and Sages of the Law to their aſſiſtance as they ſhould think fit ſhould upon Complaint correct the Errors of the Exchequer,
and that was without Limitation, as to Judgments given before the Statute as well as after, though a Writ of Error lay then from Exchecquer Judgments to Parliament.
